Title: A Mean-Variance Benchmark for Intertemporal Portfolio Theory 
Author-Name: JOHN H. COCHRANE  
Abstract:
  type="main"> <title type="main">ABSTRACT</title> <p>Mean-variance
 portfolio theory can apply to streams of payoffs such as dividends
 following an initial investment. This description is useful when returns
 are not independent over time and investors have nonmarketed income.
 Investors hedge their outside income streams. Then, their optimal payoff
 is split between an indexed perpetuity—the risk-free payoff—and a long-run
 mean-variance efficient payoff. “Long-run” moments sum over time as well
 as states of nature. In equilibrium, long-run expected returns vary with
 long-run market betas and outside-income betas. State-variable hedges do
 not appear.
